00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:26,320
So this is a bread and butter user retaining feature for centralized exchanges.

118
00:09:26,320 --> 00:09:32,480
You would imagine this kind of a feature will be available on every decentralized exchanges

119
00:09:32,480 --> 00:09:35,800
like Uniswap, PancakeSwap, and everywhere, right?

120
00:09:35,800 --> 00:09:37,240
But it's not actually the case.

121
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:39,720
None of them have this feature.

122
00:09:39,720 --> 00:09:42,360
And it's not because they don't want to build this.

123
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:47,400
It's actually because they're building this feature on blockchain directly requires a

124
00:09:47,400 --> 00:09:54,320
level of computation that is not available in today's blockchain because it's too expensive.

125
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:55,980
Well, why is that?

126
00:09:55,980 --> 00:09:59,960
We want to ask why blockchains are actually this expensive, right?

127
00:09:59,960 --> 00:10:05,260
Well, it is actually deeply rooted in how blockchains work today.

128
00:10:05,260 --> 00:10:10,800
So blockchain is operated by something called distributed consensus, and you have a lot

129
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:16,840
of different nodes in the blockchain network, and everyone is computing the same thing,

130
00:10:16,840 --> 00:10:23,320
so they can reach agreement on certain computation result and kind of move the blockchain forward.

131
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:28,880
So let's say we have this two-node blockchain where we have Alice and Bob here, and Alice

132
00:10:28,880 --> 00:10:35,440
is trying to compute the result of this multiplication equation, and then Alice is now trying to

133
00:10:35,440 --> 00:10:39,200
convince Bob this is actually the correct result.

134
00:10:39,200 --> 00:10:41,360
So what does Bob do here?

135
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:48,000
Well, the only way for Bob to actually reach consensus with Alice is to do the computation again.

136
00:10:49,640 --> 00:10:59,040
So this is okay, but this is actually problematic because a very simple kind of a computation

137
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:04,440
that is, let's say you want to swap token A to token B on blockchain is now actually

138
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:08,680
replicated a million times on blockchains like Ethereum because you have actually a

139
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:14,400
million different kind of nodes in Ethereum, and that is why replicated computing is making

140
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:17,400
blockchain extremely expensive to use.

141
00:11:17,400 --> 00:11:21,370
Well, so how do we solve this?

142
00:11:21,370 --> 00:11:27,650
Well, we can solve this by using a new concept called verifiable computing.

143
00:11:27,650 --> 00:11:32,250
In verifiable computing, you have different roles in the computing process.

144
00:11:32,250 --> 00:11:39,590
So you have Alice as not only the computing provider, but also a proof generator.

145
00:11:39,590 --> 00:11:45,150
So Alice is not only just doing the computing, but also generates a mathematical piece, a

146
00:11:45,150 --> 00:11:49,810
magical piece of mathematical proof called zero-knowledge proof.

147
00:11:49,810 --> 00:11:56,630
So the zero-knowledge proof is a very magical thing here that Alice can send to Bob here

148
00:11:56,630 --> 00:12:00,950
so that Bob can verify the computation is done correctly without actually rerunning

149
00:12:00,950 --> 00:12:03,470
the computation again.

150
00:12:03,470 --> 00:12:08,910
And this is very important because no matter how complex the original computation is, the

151
00:12:09,670 --> 00:12:16,270
verification cost is always tiny and the verification latency is always very low.

152
00:12:16,270 --> 00:12:20,670
And with this new primitive, we can build new kind of blockchains and even new kind

153
00:12:20,670 --> 00:12:26,470
of blockchain applications because now, you know, we don't actually need to run everything

154
00:12:26,470 --> 00:12:28,430
on blockchain themselves.

155
00:12:28,430 --> 00:12:35,550
We can actually offload very complex and heavy computation away from blockchain to this off-chain

156
00:12:35,550 --> 00:12:38,310
environment that we built called Brevis.

157
00:12:38,310 --> 00:12:43,470
And inside of Brevis, you can actually do the computation but also generate a zero-knowledge

158
00:12:43,470 --> 00:12:48,550
proof and you can bring the zero-knowledge proof back to the blockchain and the blockchain

159
00:12:48,550 --> 00:12:53,590
can use the computation result as if the entire computation happened on blockchain directly.

160
00:12:53,590 --> 00:12:59,670
The most important thing here is that this entire process does not actually introduce

161
00:12:59,670 --> 00:13:04,790
any additional trust assumptions and is as secure as if you're just doing everything

162
00:13:04,790 --> 00:13:09,710
on blockchain directly but at the same time, extremely low cost because the blockchains

163
00:13:09,710 --> 00:13:17,630
themselves are just verifying the computation result instead of actually doing the computation.

164
00:13:17,630 --> 00:13:24,990
So Brevis is actually massively used in production today and we have great adoption across, for

165
00:13:24,990 --> 00:13:31,790
example, the DeFi ecosystem and some of the biggest attacks today like PancakeSwap, Uniswap,

166
00:13:32,790 --> 00:13:38,830
are using us to build their user customisation and intelligent DeFi features.

